text: My thoughts: Javier Bardem is amazing actor, I am glad he was given a different look-he fits in with this franchise, but is not too similar to the skeletons, zombies, or Davey Jone's crew. With the time taken into making this film, along with the return of characters and those related, it is clear this film will have a good amount going on. Not simply a race to a fountain with no real super-natural force beside one big scene (the mermaids) and a magic sword/ship. This is going to be "death in his wake" and battle time, for one reason or another. Stronger acting, not the very mellow, stand in blackbeard we got in 4. Ghosts, how do you stop them, hmmmm? The mood is also far more the tone of 1, 2, and 3. In conclusion, from this, I believe this franchised has worked to learn, instead of simply hoping for another hit. I expect better 3D hopefully (don't be cheap disney) as well.

text: I'm so exited for Pirates Of The Caribbean 576. Seriously, just give up. Nobody likes this shitty series. The first film was loads of fun, the second and third made no goddamn sense and the fourth was just a shitty action movie. You're flogging a horse so dead its skeleton has decomposed. Realistically, many people will pay to see it, but that's just because they loved the first film and over-optimistically hope for a return to form, which will probably never happen. You'll get terrible reviews and you'll try again every five years, further embarrassing Disney and shitting all over the first film. It's seriously difficult to enjoy the first film knowing it's part of the same series as three (and probably now four) utter pieces of shit. Just use your budget to make a great original film. You'll probably get the same amount of money either way, but this way you'll have integrity. If you absolutely must  turn this series into James Bond, just understand why everyone loves the first film. It's not because of its action, its fantasy, its deep and complex characters, or its many deep and complex subplots. It's simply because it's loads of fun. When you try to make a POTC film driven by those former elements, you epically fail. Please stop trying to be like Star Wars.

text: Ok so as I am watching this figure walk through the ship cutting down people, my immeadiate thought was that Will Turner had finally lost his mind and gone down the same road davey jones did, hunting down ships to add to his ranks. His face being hidden his long flowing hair always hiding him. leaving us to wonder. But then they show what must obviously be Will Turners son behind bars...on a british naval ship... And I then think, OH this isn't a monsterous attack, This is William coming to rescue his son. And as the music plays in a hauntingly similar fashion to davey jones theme, the figure walks down the steps and the look on that kids face, as though hes seeing someone he never expected to see.... and then bam the sword into the sparrow flyer... I was waiting for williams face to show behind it. But NO! For a split second we see what appears to be wills father bootstrape bill, and what looks like the sea life growth on his face returned. Its only when he steps into the light and says his name do we realize... this is someone new and this is a whole different game now. THATS how you do a mother f*cking trailer!

text: There's a link to an old Easter Egg here, if you think about it.  DAVY: "Do you fear death?" JACK: "You have no idea..."  Davy wasn't death; he simply transported the dead at sea to an eternal resting place (which later became more of a prison due to Davy's corruption and inability to keep doing his job). Davy bargained with men to delay their meeting with "Death".  Captain Salazar may, in fact, be Death (or his errand boy) coming for Jack. Given how many people have grudges with Sparrow, and how many stories surround him, it's quite possible he's been alive for several centuries eluding Death.

Tone also seems to be much darker, which is welcome (many forget the old movies had their share of horror moments, not just action/comedy). I like that it seems to be going back to the epic supernatural elements, like there were in the first three films. OST tried to backpedal on that, and it made it a visually uninteresting slog, after an entire trilogy of amazing sights and sounds. My fingers will be crossed for this one.

text: Hey Disney, here is a short list of things that I would like to see in a Pirates Of the Caribean movie.  1)A Sea Serpent. Retro scary cool monster.  2) Atlantis. Heck, you made up a whole language for the place in that animated movie. Might as well use it for atlantean characters. Adds world building atmosphere, internally advertises your properties, and the internet will eat up the "Oh, is Captain Jack in the same continuity as a Disney Cartoon?" stuff.  3) Tritons. No, not Ariel's dad. Look it up then make it up. You can make up a warrior race of fish people. Aqua Klingons. Have fun with that.  4)Grace O'mally references. When we historically have a Pirate Queen, it may be cool to have her in the film (she died in the 1600s, so add some magic to that), have a kickass grand daughter carrying on the family name, or have Jack hunt the treasure she left behind.  5) Search for the treasure of Sinbad. The movie writes itself. Get Deltoro to direct and he will stuff the film with Harrihousen monsters.  6)The likelihood of you going to japan is high for film novelty, so here are two things. A) Did you know off the northern coast of Japan there is a pyramid-like staircase leading deep underwater? Make up something with that. B) Did you know that eating Japanese mermaids can either turn you immortal or into a butt-ugly berserk monster? Story kinda writes itself. Free advertising if you have Jack Sparrow fighting a ninja.  7) Odyssey waters. You got Circi, Sirens, greek myth stuff all over the place, Add some Harpies that can fly and swarm a pirate ship and maybe have the treasure be the tomb of Poseidon or something else to make up. The last sword of Hephestus? Hm? Just remeber in the rich myth to have plenty of contemporary Mediterranean people and pirates.  ((Jeeze, at this point just an animated series sounds better))  8) Baron Munchausen. Does not matter how he got there, but forcing Jack Sparrow to be someone else's straight man would be a great way to cap the series as he competes with the master of ridiculous legendary feats

text: I cannot believe it is here! I thought it was a fan-trailer at first. Glad to see its coming, though I have to say they are going darker -¬†that I don't like about it - but a veteran movie go-er I know that things are not always as they seem. Sure hope its not in the theme of the fourth one. I didn't enjoy that one as I did the others. Then again going completely back to the fun loving elements of the first three would in itself be a mistake. I just hold great hopes that it ends the series on the great note it began on. So So many films series start out great but only get darker and darker and ultimately ruin - for me at least - what¬†was once so great about them. I still hold out hope that Will and Elizabeth¬†return one last time, too. Then again, my hopes for this film are no greater than those - and the fears that I hold -¬†for the next HTTYD film. We can only go see and find out! True fans will go see it even if it turns out we don't like it. We love the old enough to give the new a try.

Supperdude9  I just look at the Rocky series with a set of, I don't know, awe, and sad eyes.  Sure, it's inspirational, sure it's a good movie series, and it deserved its awards.  It's just hard for me to ignore what else happened in the movies.    Too bad his trainer failed him in the third movie, having him go soft by setting up lollipop fights so he could retain his title.  Too bad his people failed him by Rocky 5 and he lost his fortune.  Rocky Balboa had the potential.  It was never utilized by the proper people.  When you get right down to it, going by stats, Rocky's time in the boxing limelight would have been... uneventful.  He has a weak record in the indies.  He got beat by Apollo in Apollo/Rocky 1.  Barely won Apollo/Rocky 2.  Had lollipop opponents to keep his title.  Got beat by Clubber.  Beat Clubber.  Beat Drago.  Fell from grace, and couldn't compete in the ring after that for the title for a few years.  Got another shot against Dixon, lost that.  Think about that.  He had THREE notable professional wins.  THREE.  Two were title wins, and the third was essentially for revenge on Drago.    Rocky's tirade against Mickey was justified.  If he had his shot, had been in his prime since day one, imagine the title reigns.  Imagine how far he could have gone.  If he had the proper people around him, he would have been the absolute best.  People around him kept failing him.  The "love" he gets from the crowd is solely because he is a novelty.  An underdog.  Not because he's the best, but because he still has that sideshow tag Apollo put on him since Rocky 1.  If Apollo did not have pride, in Rocky 1 and in this scene, Rocky would have forever been a mere footnote in the indie scene.  Apollo could not let go of his investments for his big fight.  Apollo could not let go of his pride and that cost him his title.     If Apollo did not do any of that, maybe he wouldn't have taken on Drago.  Maybe he wouldn't have died in the ring.    As much as the Rocky series is heralded for being about triumph, it's also full of tragedy.
